We must “extract” the tax‐amount information (the “tax_amount” field) from every transaction that actually records a tax charge and then sum all the numbers. In our sample “problem to solve” table many rows do not have a tax field (for deposits, purchases, expenses, etc.) only the Sale–type transactions show a tax amount (together with after‐tax amount, etc.). In our “task to solve” we go through each row that (by its “type” field and non–empty “tax_amount” value) contributes a tax expense. (For example, the row with id “Sale20240102001” shows tax_amount = 2658.54, while the row “Sale20240104004” gives 2379.68, and so on.)

Thus the tax expense item (the total tax charged on the sales transactions that appears in the income statement) is 243,988.48.
